## 5. Anticipated Viva Questions & Answers

### Matrix & Memory Management

**Q1: Why do you use `new` and `delete` instead of `std::vector`?**
> Project requirement: demonstrate manual dynamic memory management, which is a core DSA skill. Vectors hide the allocation/deallocation complexity.

**Q2: What is the Rule of Three? Why does your Matrix need it?**
> If a class manages a resource (heap memory), it must define: (1) Destructor, (2) Copy Constructor, (3) Copy Assignment Operator. Without them, copying a Matrix would give two objects pointing to the same memory → double-free crash.

**Q3: What happens if you don't have a copy constructor?**
> The compiler generates a **shallow copy** — both matrices would share the same `data` pointer. When one is destroyed, it frees the memory. The other now has a **dangling pointer** → undefined behavior / crash.

**Q4: Why is Matrix a template?**
> So it can store any type: `Matrix<Pixel>` for images, `Matrix<int>` for Sobel kernels, `Matrix<double>` for future use. One implementation, multiple data types.

**Q5: What is the time complexity of accessing `mat(i, j)`?**
> O(1) — direct pointer dereference: `data[i][j]`. First dereference gets the row pointer, second gets the element.

**Q6: Why row-major `T**` instead of a flat 1D array?**
> `T**` gives intuitive 2D access `data[i][j]`. A flat array would need index calculation `data[i * cols + j]`. Both are O(1), but `T**` is clearer for educational purposes.

### Image Processing

**Q7: Why PPM format instead of PNG or JPEG?**
> PPM is the simplest uncompressed image format — just a header and raw RGB bytes. No external libraries needed to read/write it, which satisfies our "no OpenCV" constraint.

**Q8: What does the grayscale formula represent?**
> ITU-R BT.601 luminance: `0.299R + 0.587G + 0.114B`. These weights reflect human eye sensitivity — we see green most (0.587), then red (0.299), then blue (0.114). Equal weights (R+G+B)/3 would look wrong.

**Q9: How does Sobel edge detection work?**
> It computes the **gradient** (rate of change) of pixel intensity. Two 3×3 kernels detect horizontal and vertical edges separately. The magnitude `√(Gx² + Gy²)` gives overall edge strength. Strong edges appear bright, flat areas appear dark.

**Q10: What is convolution?**
> Sliding a kernel (small matrix) over an image, at each position multiplying overlapping values and summing them. It's a mathematical operation that extracts features (edges, blur, sharpen) depending on the kernel values.

**Q11: How do you handle image boundaries in Sobel?**
> Clamping — if a neighbor index is out of bounds, we clamp it to the nearest valid index. So edge pixels repeat the border value.

### Huffman Coding (Most Important!)

**Q12: What is Huffman coding?**
> A lossless data compression algorithm that assigns variable-length binary codes to symbols based on their frequency. Frequent symbols get short codes, rare symbols get long codes. This reduces the total number of bits needed.

**Q13: Why is it lossless?**
> Every original byte is perfectly recoverable. The Huffman code is a **prefix code** — no code is a prefix of another — so decoding is unambiguous. We store the frequency table in the file, so the decoder rebuilds the exact same tree.

**Q14: Walk me through how you build the Huffman tree.**
> 1. Count frequency of each byte (0-255) in the raw data
> 2. Create a leaf HuffmanNode for each byte that appears
> 3. Insert all leaves into a MinHeap (priority queue)
> 4. Repeat: extract two nodes with lowest frequency, create a parent node with freq = sum, insert parent back
> 5. When one node remains, it's the root

**Q15: Why do you use a MinHeap?**
> To efficiently get the two lowest-frequency nodes at each step. Extract-min is O(log n), and we do it 2×(n-1) times → total O(n log n). Without a heap, finding the minimum would be O(n) each time → O(n²) total.

**Q16: How does your MinHeap work internally?**
> It's a **complete binary tree** stored as a dynamic array. For node at index `i`: parent = `(i-1)/2`, left child = `2i+1`, right child = `2i+2`. HeapifyUp (after insert) swaps with parent while smaller. HeapifyDown (after extract) swaps with smaller child.

**Q17: How do you encode data using the Huffman tree?**
> After building the tree, I do a DFS: going left adds '0', going right adds '1'. At each leaf, the accumulated path is that byte's code. Then I replace each byte in the original data with its code, packing bits into bytes.

**Q18: How do you handle the "padding bits" issue?**
> The total compressed bits might not be a multiple of 8. I calculate `paddingBits = compressedBytes×8 - totalBits` and store it in the file header. During decompression, I stop reading after `totalBits` bits.

**Q19: What is the compression rate you achieve?**
> Depends on the image. Images with many repeated colors compress better. The formula is `(1 - compressed/original) × 100%`. The project requires ≥ 30%.

**Q20: Why does grayscale compress better than color?**
> Grayscale images only have ~256 possible pixel values (0-255 repeated 3 times), while color images can have up to 256³ = 16.7M unique RGB combinations. Fewer unique values → more repetition → better Huffman compression.

**Q21: How do you deserialize back to `Matrix<Pixel>`?**
> The decoded byte array is in R,G,B,R,G,B... order. I read 3 consecutive bytes, create a Pixel(R,G,B), and place it in the matrix at position (row, col).

**Q22: What is the time complexity of Huffman compression?**
> - Frequency counting: O(n) where n = total bytes
> - Tree building: O(k log k) where k = unique byte values (max 256)
> - Encoding: O(n × average_code_length)
> - Total: **O(n)** since k ≤ 256 is constant

**Q23: What if all bytes are the same value?**
> Edge case! If uniqueCount == 1, I assign a single code `"0"` (1 bit per byte). The tree has only one leaf node. This still compresses well: 1 bit vs 8 bits = 87.5% compression.

### General / Architecture

**Q24: Why don't you use OpenCV or any image library?**
> Project constraint. This forces us to implement everything manually using DSA concepts — file parsing, matrix operations, pixel manipulation, compression — which is the educational purpose.

**Q25: Why Qt for the GUI?**
> Qt is a powerful C++ GUI framework. It provides widgets (buttons, labels), layouts, signals/slots for event handling, and built-in image display. It integrates naturally with C++ code.

**Q26: How does `displayImage()` work?**
> 1. Iterate over `Matrix<Pixel>`, copy each pixel's RGB values into a `QImage` scanline buffer
> 2. Convert `QImage` → `QPixmap` 
> 3. Scale to fit the canvas while keeping aspect ratio
> 4. Set as the QLabel's pixmap

**Q27: What design pattern does ImageProcessor use?**
> **Static utility class** — all methods are `static`, no instance state. It's essentially a namespace of pure functions. Each method takes input, returns new output (non-destructive).

**Q28: Why does Image store `Matrix<Pixel>*` (pointer) instead of `Matrix<Pixel>` (value)?**
> So we can have a "null" state (`pixels = nullptr`) when no image is loaded. `isLoaded()` checks this. Also allows deferred allocation — the default constructor creates an empty Image without allocating a matrix.

**Q29: What happens when I click a button?**
> Qt's **signal-slot mechanism**: `QPushButton::clicked` signal is connected to a slot (e.g., `MainWindow::onGrayscale`). When the button emits `clicked()`, Qt automatically calls the connected slot function.

**Q30: How is your project structured?**
> ```
> Pixel.h          — Data: single RGB pixel (value type)
> Matrix.h         — DSA: template 2D matrix with manual memory
> Image.h/.cpp     — I/O: PPM P6 file reader/writer wrapping Matrix<Pixel>
> ImageProcessor.h/.cpp — Algorithms: grayscale, Sobel, scaling
> HuffmanCompressor.h/.cpp — Compression: MinHeap + Huffman tree
> MainWindow.h/.cpp — GUI: Qt interface connecting everything
> main.cpp         — Entry point: creates QApplication + MainWindow
> ```

---

## Quick Reference: Key Numbers to Remember

| Fact | Value |
|------|-------|
| Pixel size | 3 bytes (R + G + B) |
| Raw image size | W × H × 3 bytes |
| Huffman tree nodes | max 256 leaves + 255 internal = 511 nodes |
| MinHeap operations | O(log n) insert/extract |
| Sobel kernel size | 3×3 = 9 multiplications per pixel |
| BT.601 weights | R=0.299, G=0.587, B=0.114 |
| PPM magic number | "P6" (binary), "P3" (ASCII) |
| .huf magic number | "HUF" |
| Target compression | ≥ 30% |

